Honestly at first I thought it was a hiding mountain lion who had spotted us. (There are warning signs at this park of the possibility of encountering a mountain lion 😬)
But thankfully we finally saw the culprit, this  Egyptian Goose who had made himself comfortable on the rooftop of a gazebo! 
I sighed in relief!

Whenever I used to think about seeing a Snowy Owl for the first time, I always imagined it would be in Canada or Alaska or somewhere in the middle of the arctic in the freezing snowing cold. Never did I ever imagine I’d see one right here in Southern California, just minutes away, in a local neighborhood. 
How lucky us locals  are to have such a beautiful unexpected visitor! Her origins are unknown and it’s a mystery as to how she got here. Last report of one in Southern California was 100 years ago! 
I’m just so happy I got to see a Snowy Owl for the first time ever.  I hope the next time I see one, it’ll be in Canada or Alaska with a snowy landscape!

This past weekend I did something different and joined @pasadenaaudubon on their “Butterflying for Birders” walk! Although the weather was a bit gloomy and there wasn’t much butterfly activity, we did manage to see the rare Gorgon Copper Butterfly! I also got to meet @omgvinita who I’ve been following on IG for awhile. Her humorous and light hearted content is so relatable to me, being south Asian, plus she’s a birder!! 
Please checkout her content, it definitely relates to anyone regardless of culture. 

I had such a great time on this walk, looking forward to joining more in the future!

I just could not believe my eyes when I saw thousands of Monarch Butterflies hanging in clusters from eucalyptus trees! 
Monarch butterflies are the only butterflies in the world that do a two way migration like birds. Some fly as much as 3,000 miles to get to their winter home! 

Nature is indeed amazing!!

Lifer Alert!! 
So extremely excited to have finally seen and photograph a Yellow Billed Magpie! 
These unique looking birds are only found in California in certain areas. The only other magpies found in North America are Black Billed Magpies, which I’ve seen in 2019 during a trip to the Grand Tetons. 
One of my goals this year is to see and photograph as many birds that I’ve never seen before as I can, so this was a good start for the first week of the new year!

It’s become sort of a tradition at the start of every new year, to visit the Brandts Cormorants that make their home at the edge of a cliff overlooking the ocean. So far it seems they’re off to a slow start as they’ve just begun to claim their spots to build their nests.  It’s amazing how they go out to the sea to find nesting materials, so fun to watch them fly back with their new home decor  too!
